t's also not entirely<br />clear what the type size even is. Usually a byte, but I don't think<br />there is any guarantee of it at all.<br /><br />Use "bool" mainly as a return type from functions that return<br />true/false, and maybe as local variables in functions.<br /><br />Maybe using single-bit bitfield with "bool" as the base type might<br />work, but the normal thing we tend to do is to just make sure the base<br />type is unsigned. It's a tiny bit more typing, but it's very<br />unambiguous what is going on, and you can specify the base type as you<br />wish and as it makes sense for packing etc.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
